  "prompt": "Why does Jeep not make a small capacity (2 liter) turbo diesel engine for the Wrangler?",
  "response": "There could be several reasons why Jeep hasn't introduced a small capacity turbo diesel engine for the Wrangler:\n\n1. Emissions regulations\n- Diesel engines face stricter emissions standards in the US\n- Developing and certifying a small diesel engine can be costly\n\n2. Cost considerations\n- Diesel engines are typically more expensive to manufacture\n- Developing a new engine platform requires significant investment\n\n3. Market demand\n- Gasoline engines are still more popular in the US market\n- Diesel's fuel efficiency advantage has decreased with modern gasoline engines\n\n4. Existing diesel option\n- Jeep currently offers a 3.0L V6 EcoDiesel in some models\n- This might satisfy their diesel market segment\n\n5. Technical challenges\n- Packaging a diesel engine in the Wrangler's compact engine bay\n- Balancing performance, fuel economy, and emissions requirements\n\n6. Weight considerations\n- Diesel engines are typically heavier, which could impact the Wrangler's off-road capabilities\n\nWhile these reasons might explain the current situation, Jeep could potentially develop a small diesel engine in the future if market conditions and technology make it more attractive.",
